    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Polaria is the world's northernmost aquarium and an Arctic experience centre, located at Hjalmar Johansens gate 12 in central Tromsø. <strong>The building, completed in 1998, was designed to resemble ice floes pushed ashore by the Arctic Ocean</strong> — five angled concrete sections stacked in a wedge form that has become a landmark on the Tromsø waterfront. The facility is operated by the Polaria Foundation, whose stated mission is to communicate research from the Arctic and sub-Arctic regions to a general audience.</p>
    <p>The centre houses <strong>seven seals across two species — three bearded seals, three harbour seals, and one ringed seal</strong> — in a recently expanded pool that is three times larger than its predecessor, with panoramic windows and an outdoor balcony. Daily feeding and training sessions at 10:30, 12:30, and 15:30 allow visitors to observe the animals at close range. The aquarium sections contain Arctic fish species including cod, halibut, wolffish, king crab, and jellyfish. Interactive exhibitions, developed in partnership with scientists from the Fram — High North Research Centre for Climate and the Environment, cover climate change, the Svalbard food web, and marine environmental toxins.</p>
    <p>A panoramic theatre inside the building screens three films on rotation: one documenting the Northern Lights over the Tromsø region, one covering the glaciers and mountain landscapes of Svalbard, and one providing a behind-the-scenes look at Polaria's animal care and aquarium operations. <strong>Polaria underwent a major expansion completed in 2025</strong>, enlarging the seal habitat and adding new interactive exhibition space with natural daylight. The museum shop carries Arctic-themed merchandise. Opening hours vary by season: daily 10:00–17:00 from 1 June to 31 August, and 10:00–16:00 from 1 September to 31 May.</p>
